  }), "\n", React.createElement(_components.p, null, "That distinction matters because when we talk about the coding capabilities of LLMs, people often collapse\nthe model, the reasoning behavior, and the agent product into one thing. But before getting into the\ncoding agent specifics, it’s important to add more context on the difference between the broader concepts,\nthe LLMs, reasoning models, and agents."), "\n", React.createElement(_components.h2, null, "LLMs, Reasoning Models, and Agents"), "\n", React.createElement(_components.p, null, "At its core, an LLM is a next-token prediction model. A reasoning model is still an LLM, but one trained and/or\nprompted to spend more inference-time compute on intermediate reasoning, self-verification, or search over candidate\nanswers before settling on a response."), "\n", React.createElement(_components.p, null, "An agent is a layer on top of this. It’s best understood as a control loop wrapped around the model — one that,\ngiven a goal, decides what to inspect next, which tools to call, how to update state, and when to stop."), "\n", React.createElement(_components.p, null, "A rough analogy: the LLM is the engine, a reasoning model is a more powerful (and more expensive) version of that engine,\nand the agent harness is what actually drives toward a goal using whichever engine is under the hood."), "\n", React.createElement(_components.p, null, "More precisely, the key terms break down like this:"), "\n", React.createElement(_components.ul, null, "\n", React.createElement(_components.li, null, React.createElement(_components.strong, null, "LLM"), ": the raw model"), "\n", React.createElement(_components.li, null, React.createElement(_components.strong, null, "Reasoning model"), ": an LLM optimized to produce intermediate reasoning traces and verify its own outputs"), "\n", React.createElement(_components.li, null, React.createElement(_components.strong, null, "Agent"), ": a loop that repeatedly calls a model within an environment, using tools, memory, and feedback to steer toward a goal"), "\n", React.createElement(_components.li, null, React.createElement(_components.strong, null, "Agent harness"), ": the software scaffold managing context, tool use, prompts, state, and control flow around an agent"), "\n", React.createElement(_components.li, null, React.createElement(_components.strong, null, "Coding harness"), ": a task-specific agent harness built for software engineering — managing code context, tools,\nexecution, and iterative feedback"), "\n"), "\n", React.createElement(_components.p, null, "A coding harness is the narrower, specialized case; an agent harness is the broader category (OpenClaw, for instance,\nis an agent harness). Codex and Claude Code are coding harnesses."), "\n", React.createElement(_components.p, null, "A better LLM gives a reasoning model a stronger foundation, and a well-built harness gets more out of that reasoning\nmodel. That said, LLMs and reasoning models can handle coding tasks on their own — but coding is only partly about\nnext-token generation. Much of the work involves repo navigation, symbol lookup, search, diff application, test\nexecution, and error inspection. That’s what a harness is for."), "\n", React.createElement(_components.span, {
