  })), "\n", React.createElement(_components.p, null, "Instead, it separates the prompt into two tiers. The first is a stable prefix — general instructions,\ntool descriptions, and the workspace summary — that doesn’t need to be rebuilt from scratch each time.\nThe second tier covers the dynamic parts that do update every turn: short-term memory, the recent transcript,\nand the new user request."), "\n", React.createElement(_components.p, null, "The caching insight is simple: if the stable prefix hasn’t meaningfully changed, reuse it.\nThere’s no reason to reprocess the same context repeatedly when only a small slice of it is actually new."), "\n", React.createElement(_components.h3, null, "3. Tool Access and Use"), "\n", React.createElement(_components.p, null, "Tool access is where the system stops feeling like a chatbot and starts feeling like an agent."), "\n", React.createElement(_components.p, null, "A plain model can suggest a command in prose — but a model running inside a coding harness should actually execute\nthat command and return the results, rather than leaving the user to run it manually and paste the output back in."), "\n", React.createElement(_components.p, null, "Rather than letting the model improvise arbitrary syntax, the harness exposes a pre-defined set of named tools with\nexplicit inputs and clear boundaries: list files, read a file, search, run a shell command, write a file, and so on.\n(That said, something like Python’s subprocess.call can be included, giving the agent a wide range of shell commands\nthrough a single, controlled interface.)"), "\n", React.createElement(_components.p, null, "The tool-use flow is illustrated in the figure below."), "\n", React.createElement(_components.span, {
